- The input signal $S_i$ is fed into the differencing node, where it is reduced by the feedback signal $S_{fb}$, producing the error signal $S_\epsilon$.
- This error signal undergoes amplification by the basic amplifier, resulting in the output signal $S_o$.
- The output signal then passes through the feedback network, creating the feedback signal $S_{fb}$.
- The feedback signal is subsequently returned to the differencing node, impacting the subsequent amplification cycle.

Overall System Function:
The core function of this system is to deliver controlled amplification of the input signal while ensuring stability via negative feedback. The feedback lowers the system's overall gain to $A = \frac{a}{1 + af}$, termed the closed-loop gain, which aids in stabilizing the amplifier and minimizing distortion and noise.

Figure 8.1 Ideal feedback configuration.

Substituting (8.2) into (8.3) yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
S_{\epsilon}=S_{i}-f S_{o} \tag{8.4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Inserting (8.4) into (8.1) results in

$$
S_{o}=a S_{i}-a f S_{o}
$$

therefore

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{S_{o}}{S_{i}}=A=\frac{a}{1+a f} \tag{8.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 8.5 is the key equation for negative feedback circuits, where $A$ represents the overall gain with feedback applied. ($A$ is commonly referred to as the closed-loop gain.)

It is beneficial to define a parameter $T$ known as the loop gain, such that

$$
\begin{equation*}
T=a f \tag{8.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{S_{o}}{S_{i}}=A=\frac{a}{1+T} \tag{8.7}
\end{equation*}
$$

$T$ represents the total gain around the feedback loop. If $T \gg 1$, then, from (8.5), the gain $A$ is approximated by

$$
\begin{equation*}
A \simeq \frac{1}{f} \tag{8.8}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, for substantial loop gain $T$, the amplifier's overall gain is governed by the feedback transfer function $f$. Since the feedback network typically consists of stable, passive components, the value of $f$ is well-defined, ensuring a stable overall amplifier gain.

The feedback loop functions by making $S_{fb}$ nearly equal to $S_{i}$. This is accomplished by amplifying the difference $S_{\epsilon}=S_{i}-S_{fb}$, thereby minimizing the error signal $S_{\epsilon}$. This can be demonstrated by substituting (8.5) into (8.4), yielding

$$
S_{\epsilon}=S_{i}-f \frac{a S_{i}}{1+a f}
$$

leading to

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{S_{\epsilon}}{S_{i}}=\frac{1}{1+a f}=\frac{1}{1+T} \tag{8.9}
\end{equation*}
$$

As $T$ significantly exceeds 1, $S_{\epsilon}$ becomes much smaller than $S_{i}$. Additionally, substituting (8.5) into (8.2) gives

$$
S_{f b}=f S_{i} \frac{a}{1+a f}
$$

thus

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{S_{f b}}{S_{i}}=\frac{T}{1+T} \tag{8.10}
\end{equation*}
$$

If $T \gg 1$, then $S_{fb}$ is roughly equivalent to $S_{i}$. In other words, the feedback signal $S_{fb}$ is a close replica of the input signal. Given that $S_{fb}$ and $S_{o}$ are directly related by (8.2), it follows that if $|f|<1$, then $S_{o}$ is an amplified version of $S_{i}$. This is the primary objective of a feedback amplifier.

