In the majority of practical scenarios, the gain $a$ of the fundamental amplifier is not precisely defined. It relies on factors such as temperature, the operating conditions of the active device, and transistor characteristics. As previously discussed, the negative-feedback loop diminishes fluctuations in the overall amplifier gain caused by variations in $a$. This phenomenon can be analyzed by differentiating equation (8.5), resulting in

$$
\frac{d A}{d a}=\frac{(1+a f)-a f}{(1+a f)^{2}}
$$

which simplifies to

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d A}{d a}=\frac{1}{(1+a f)^{2}} \tag{8.11}
