description:The circuit illustrates a shunt-shunt feedback configuration comprising a basic amplifier and a feedback network. The transresistance and transconductance are depicted through equations involving these components.
Figure 8.9 Shunt-shunt feedback configuration.

Substituting (8.32) into (8.34) results in

$$
\frac{v_{o}}{a}=i_{i}-f v_{o}
$$

Rearranging the terms, we obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{o}}{i_{i}}=\frac{a}{1+a f}=A \tag{8.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

The ideal feedback equation remains applicable. Note that while $a$ and $f$ have resistance and conductance dimensions, the loop gain $T=a f$ is dimensionless, which is consistently true.

In this setup, if the source impedance $z_{s}$ is finite, the input current $i_{i}$ divides between $z_{s}$ and the amplifier input, causing the ratio $v_{o} / i_{i}$ to be less precisely defined than (8.35) suggests. Therefore, the full advantages of negative feedback for a shunt-shunt feedback amplifier are realized when $z_{s} \gg Z_{i}$, approaching a current-source drive.

The input impedance of the circuit in Fig. 8.9 can be determined using (8.32) and (8.35), giving

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{\epsilon}=\frac{i_{i}}{1+a f} \tag{8.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

The input impedance $Z_{i}$ with feedback is

$$
\begin{equation*}
Z_{i}=\frac{v_{i}}{i_{i}} \tag{8.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting (8.36) into (8.37) results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
Z_{i}=\frac{v_{i}}{i_{\epsilon}} \frac{1}{1+a f}=\frac{z_{i}}{1+T} \tag{8.38}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, shunt feedback at the input decreases the amplifier input impedance by $(1+T)$. This is universally true.

It can be easily demonstrated that the output impedance in this scenario is

$$
\begin{equation*}
Z_{o}=\frac{z_{o}}{1+T} \tag{8.39}
\end{equation*}
$$

as previously noted for shunt feedback at the output.
Shunt-shunt feedback has enhanced this amplifier's performance as a transresistance amplifier. The transfer function $v_{o} / i_{i}$ has been stabilized, and both $Z_{i}$ and $Z_{o}$ have been reduced.

The initial shunt-shunt feedback amplifier of Fig. 8.9 can now be represented as shown in Fig. 8.10a using (8.35), (8.38), and (8.39). As the forward gain $a$ approaches infinity, the equivalent circuit converges to that of Fig. 8.10b, which is an ideal transresistance amplifier.

