- The primary function of this two-port network is to relate input and output voltages and currents via the y-parameters. The y-parameters dictate how the input current \( i_1 \) and output current \( i_2 \) are influenced by the input voltage \( v_1 \) and output voltage \( v_2 \). This representation is advantageous for analyzing and designing circuits with interconnected networks by simplifying intricate interactions into linear equations.

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
i_{1}=y_{11} v_{1}+y_{12} v_{2} & \\
i_{2}=y_{21} v_{1}+y_{22} v_{2} & \\
y_{11}=\left.\frac{i_{1}}{v_{1}}\right|_{v_{2}=0} & y_{12}=\left.\frac{i_{1}}{v_{2}}\right|_{v_{1}=0} \\
y_{21}=\left.\frac{i_{2}}{v_{1}}\right|_{v_{2}=0} & y_{22}=\left.\frac{i_{2}}{v_{2}}\right|_{v_{1}=0}
\end{array}
$$

Figure 8.14 The $y$-parameter representation of a two-port.

Summation of currents at the output yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
0=\left(y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}\right) v_{i}+\left(y_{L}+y_{22 a}+y_{22 f}\right) v_{o} \tag{8.47}
\end{equation*}
$$

It is helpful to define

$$
\begin{gather*}
y_{i}=y_{S}+y_{11 a}+y_{11 f}  \tag{8.48}\\
y_{o}=y_{L}+y_{22 a}+y_{22 f} \tag{8.49}
\end{gather*}
$$

Solving (8.46) and (8.47) by applying (8.48) and (8.49) results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{o}}{i_{s}}=\frac{-\left(y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}\right)}{y_{i} y_{o}-\left(y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}\right)\left(y_{12 a}+y_{12 f}\right)} \tag{8.50}
\end{equation*}
$$

Rearranging the equation by dividing by $y_{i} y_{o}$ converts it into the ideal feedback equation of (8.35), resulting in

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{o}}{i_{s}}=\frac{\frac{-\left(y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}\right)}{y_{i} y_{o}}}{1+\frac{-\left(y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}\right)}{y_{i} y_{o}}\left(y_{12 a}+y_{12 f}\right)} \tag{8.51}
\end{equation*}
$$

Comparing (8.51) with (8.35) yields

$$
\begin{align*}
& a=-\frac{y_{21 a}+y_{21 f}}{y_{i} y_{o}}  \tag{8.52}\\
& f=y_{12 a}+y_{12 f} \tag{8.53}
\end{align*}
$$

At this stage, various approximations can be made to significantly simplify the calculations. Initially, we assume that the signal transmitted by the basic amplifier is vastly superior to the signal fed forward by the feedback network. Considering the amplifying gain (typically substantial) of the former and the loss in the latter, this is generally a valid assumption. This implies that

$$
\begin{equation*}
\left|y_{21 a}\right| \gg\left|y_{21 f}\right| \tag{8.54}
\end{equation*}
$$

Secondly, we assume that the signal fed back by the feedback network is much more significant than the signal fed back through the basic amplifier. Given the typically low reverse transmission in most active devices, including the basic amplifier, this assumption is usually quite accurate. This implies that

$$
\begin{equation*}
\left|y_{12 a}\right| \ll\left|y_{12 f}\right| \tag{8.55}
\end{equation*}
$$

Applying (8.54) and (8.55) to (8.51) results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v_{o}}{i_{s}}=A \simeq \frac{\frac{-y_{21 a}}{y_{i} y_{o}}}{1+\left(\frac{-y_{21 a}}{y_{i} y_{o}}\right) y_{12 f}} \tag{8.56}
\end{equation*}
$$

Comparing (8.56) with (8.35) provides

$$
\begin{align*}
a & =-\frac{y_{21 a}}{y_{i} y_{o}}  \tag{8.57}\\
f & =y_{12 f} \tag{8.58}
\end{align*}
$$

The circuit representation of (8.57) and (8.58) can be obtained as follows. Equations 8.54 and 8.55 suggest that in Figure 8.13a, the feedback generator of the basic amplifier and the forward transmission generator of the feedback network can be disregarded. If this is done, the circuit can be redrawn as shown in Figure 8.13b, where the terminal admittances $y_{11 f}$ and $y_{22 f}$ of the feedback network have been incorporated into the basic amplifier, along with source and load impedances $y_{S}$ and $y_{L}$. Consequently, the new basic amplifier accounts for the loading effect of the original feedback network, and the new feedback network becomes ideal as depicted in Figure 8.9. If the transfer function of the basic amplifier in Figure 8.13b is calculated (by first removing the feedback network), the result given in (8.57) is achieved. Similarly, the transfer function of the feedback network in Figure 8.13b is given by (8.58). Thus, Figure 8.13b is a circuit representation of (8.57) and (8.58).

As Figure 8.13b directly corresponds to Figure 8.9, all the results derived in Section 8.4.2 for Figure 8.9 can be applied now. The loading effect of the feedback network on the basic amplifier is accounted for by simply shunting the input and output with $y_{11 f}$ and $y_{22 f}$, respectively. As depicted in Figure 8.14, these terminal admittances of the feedback network are calculated with the other port of the network short-circuited. In practice, the loading term $y_{11 f}$ is simply obtained by shorting the output node of the amplifier and calculating the feedback circuit input admittance. Similarly, term $y_{22 f}$ is calculated by shorting the input node in the amplifier and calculating the feedback circuit output admittance. The feedback transfer function $f$ given by (8.58) is the short-circuit reverse transfer admittance of the feedback network and is defined in Figure 8.14. This is easily calculable in practice and is often obtainable through inspection. Note that the use of $y$ parameters in further calculations is not necessary. Once the circuit of Figure 8.13b is established, any convenient network analysis method may be utilized to calculate gain $a$ of the basic amplifier. We have merely used the two-port representation as a general way to illustrate how loading effects can be incorporated into the calculations.

For instance, consider the common shunt-shunt feedback circuit employing an operational amplifier shown in Figure 8.15a. The equivalent circuit is depicted in Figure 8.15b and is redrawn in Figure 8.15c to accommodate the loading effect of the feedback network on the basic amplifier. The $y$ parameters of the feedback network can be determined from Figure 8.15d.

$$
