Consider, as an example, the series-series feedback triplet of Fig. 8.18a, which serves as a broadband feedback amplifier. $R_{E 2}$ is typically a low-value resistor that samples the output current $i_{o}$, and the resulting voltage across $R_{E 2}$ is sampled by the divider $R_{F}$ and $R_{E 1}$ to generate a feedback voltage across $R_{E 1}$. Generally is common for $R_{F}$ to be significantly larger than $R_{E 1}$ and $R_{E 2}$.

The two-port theory established earlier is not directly applicable in this instance because the basic amplifier cannot be depicted by a two-port model. However, the techniques previously developed using two-port theory can be adapted with minor alterations by first acknowledging that the feedback network can be represented by a two-port, as demonstrated in 8.18 b. One challenge with this circuit is that the feedback generator $z_{12} i_{e 3}$ is located at the emitter of $Q_{1}$ and not at the input lead where it can be directly compared with $v_{s}$. This issue can be resolved by examining the small-signal equivalent of the input segment of this circuit, as shown in Fig. 8.19. For this circuit:

