\end{equation*}
$$

where

$$
\begin{align*}
& a=-\frac{h_{21 a}}{z_{i} y_{o}}  \tag{8.124}\\
& f=h_{12 f} \tag{8.125}
\end{align*}
$$

A circuit representation of $a$ in (8.124) and $f$ in (8.125) can be derived by removing the generators $h_{12 a} v_{o}$ and $h_{21} i_{i}$ from Fig. $8.23 a$, as suggested by the approximations in (8.121) and (8.122). This results in the approximate representation of Fig. $8.23 b$, where the new basic amplifier includes the loading effect of the original feedback network. As in prior examples, the circuit of Fig. $8.23 b$ represents (8.123), (8.124), and (8.125) and resembles an ideal feedback loop. Thus, all equations from Section 8.4.1 can be applied to this circuit.

For instance, consider the common series-shunt op amp circuit in Fig. 8.24, which precisely fits the described model. First, we determine the $h$ parameters of the feedback network from Fig. 8.25:

$$
\begin{align*}
