#### EXAMPLE

Assume the circuit in Fig. 8.24 is implemented using a differential amplifier with low-frequency parameters $z_{i}=100 \mathrm{k} \Omega, z_{o}=10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$, and $a_{v}=3000$. Calculate the input impedance of the feedback amplifier at low frequencies for $R_{E}=5 \mathrm{k} \Omega, R_{F}=20 \mathrm{k} \Omega$, and $z_{L}=10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$. Note that $z_{o}$ is not negligible in this case, which can occur in some applications.

This problem is best approached by first calculating the input impedance of the basic amplifier and then multiplying by $(1+T)$ as indicated by (8.25) to find the input impedance of the feedback amplifier. By inspection from Fig. 8.26, the input impedance of the basic amplifier is

$$
z_{i a}=z_{i}+R_{E} \| R_{F}=(100+5 \| 20) \mathrm{k} \Omega=104 \mathrm{k} \Omega
$$

